If the reheating is delayed due to a late-time decay of the inflaton, depending on whether $w>\frac{1}{3}$ or not, the contribution coming from reheating dynamics can increase or decrease the number of efoldings during inflation. The reason is the following. For $w>\frac{1}{3}$, the horizon radius of the Universe at recombination would have been larger than in the case of instantaneous reheating. Therefore, the largest scale of cosmological interest must have left the horizon earlier so that the number of efoldings during inflation gets larger. On the other hand, for $w<\frac{1}{3}$, the situation is the opposite, meaning that the horizon radius of the Universe at recombination would have been smaller than in the case of instantaneous reheating and a smaller number of efoldings during inflation is needed. Lastly, for $w=\frac{1}{3}$, there is no distinction between reheating and radiation domination after reheating, so there is no effect from reheating dynamics on the number of efoldings in this case. 

In Fig.~\ref{ns-l3},  for a fixed tensor-to-scalar ratio with $r=10^{-5}$ and $r=0.1$ in the upper and lower panels, respectively, we show the spectral index as a function of the coefficient of the cubic term, $\lambda_3$, depending on the reheating temperature, $T_{\rm rh}=10^2\,{\rm GeV}$, $10^9\,{\rm GeV}$, $T_{\rm max}$, and the equation of state, $w=-\frac{1}{3}, 0, \frac{2}{3}$,  during reheating. For a negative equation of state satisfying $-\frac{1}{3}\leq w<0$, the reheating period reduces significantly the number of efoldings required for solving the horizon problem, so that the smaller the reheating temperature, the smaller the value of $\lambda_3$ is favored. But, for a positive equation of state satisfying $0< w\leq 1$, the dependence on the reheating temperature gets milder.   
For a large tensor-to-scalar ratio as in the lower panel, the value of $\lambda_3$ that is consistent with the observed spectral index is insensitive to the reheating temperature or the equation of state, because the spectral index is dominated by the $\epsilon$ parameter so it is insensitive to the number of efoldings.  

In Fig.~\ref{reheat}, we also show the parameter space for $V_0$ or $r$ vs $\lambda_3$ in log scales, satisfying the observed spectral index within Planck $1\sigma$ or $2\sigma$ bands. 
