Since $\lambda_\phi$ is small at low energies, the $B-L$ Higgs tends to be light \footnote{The $B-L$ symmetry can be broken with a tree-level negative mass squared for the $B-L$ Higgs or by the Coleman-Weinberg mechanism \cite{chun}. In the latter case, the $B-L$ Higgs without non-minimal coupling was discussed in view of Planck data as an inflaton candidate \cite{CW}. } so it decays dominantly into a pair of the SM Higgs bosons, reheating the SM sector.  Then,  the reheating temperature is given by
\begin{eqnarray}
T_{\rm rh}= 0.5 \sqrt{M_P \Gamma_\phi}\approx 0.05\lambda_{H\phi} v_{B-L} \sqrt{\frac{M_P}{m_\phi}}
\end{eqnarray}
where use is made of $\Gamma_\phi\approx \frac{\lambda^2_{H\phi} v^2_{B-L}}{32\pi m_\phi}$ for $m_\phi\gg m_h$ with $m_h$ being the SM Higgs mass.  Thus, imposing the bound on the mixing angle between the $B-L$ Higgs and the SM Higgs from the Higgs signal strength, such as $|\sin\theta| \approx \frac{|\lambda_{H\phi}| v_{B-L} v}{m^2_\phi}<0.44$ \cite{Higgsfit}, we obtain the lower bound on the reheating temperature as
\begin{eqnarray}
T_{\rm rh} \lesssim (5.3\times 10^8\,{\rm GeV}) \Big(\frac{m_\phi}{v} \Big)^{3/2}.
\end{eqnarray}

Suppose that the Higgs-portal coupling $\lambda_{H\phi}$ is very small in the UV so it is generated radiatively in the presence of the gauge kinetic mixing \cite{chun}. In this case, when the Higgs mass parameter is solely from the Higgs-portal coupling after the $B-L$ breaking, we get $|\lambda_{h\phi}|=\frac{m^2_h}{v^2_{B-L}}$ \cite{chun}, which satisfies the limit from the Higgs signal strength for $v_{B-L}\gg m_h$. Therefore,  the reheating temperature  can be much smaller as follows,
\begin{eqnarray}
T_{\rm rh}\approx (3.2 \times 10^8\,{\rm GeV}) \Big(\frac{v^3}{v^2_{B-L} m_\phi} \Big)^{1/2} \ll 3.2 \times 10^8\,{\rm GeV}.
\end{eqnarray}

In Fig.~\ref{Higgs-reheat}, we show the spectral index as a function of the non-minimal coupling for several values of $h_0=1, 0.5$ and, depending on the reheating temperature, $T_{\rm rh}=100\,{\rm GeV}, 10^8\,{\rm GeV}, T_{\rm max}$ in dotted, dashed and solid lines, respectively, and the equation of state with $w=-\frac{1}{3}, 0, \frac{2}{3}$ during reheating, for the left, middle and right figures in each panel.  We also overlay in each plot the tensor-to-scalar ratio in black solid line. 
The smaller the reheating temperature, the larger parameter space satisfying the observed spectral index, in particular, the smaller the value of the non-minimal coupling is favored.  
For large values of the inflection point as in the lower panel in Fig.~\ref{Higgs-reheat}, there is a parameter space with a small non-minimal coupling where the  tensor-to-scalar ratio is close to the current limit, $r<0.10$. 


\section{Conclusions}

We have considered the inflection point inflation as one of the slow-roll inflation models that might be insensitive to trans-Planckian problems usually encountered in large field inflation models. 
We showed that the inflection point inflation predicting a small tensor-to-scalar ratio is sensitive to the inflaton couplings and the equation of state during inflation, whereas the case with a large tensor-to-scalar ratio is robust and insensitive to the reheating dynamics.  
From the examples of the SM Higgs inflation and the $B-L$ Higgs inflation where the reheating temperature is determined,  we presented the inflationary predictions for the spectral index and the tensor-to-scalar ratio, depending on the reheating dynamics. 
In particular, in the $B-L$ Higgs inflation, when the light inflaton has a small Higgs-portal coupling, the reheating temperature is small, so the reheating dynamics affects much the inflationary predictions if the equation of state deviates from radiation. 


