\section{Conclusions}

We have considered the inflection point inflation as one of the slow-roll inflation models that might be insensitive to trans-Planckian problems usually encountered in large field inflation models. 
We showed that the inflection point inflation predicting a small tensor-to-scalar ratio is sensitive to the inflaton couplings and the equation of state during inflation, whereas the case with a large tensor-to-scalar ratio is robust and insensitive to the reheating dynamics.  
From the examples of the SM Higgs inflation and the $B-L$ Higgs inflation where the reheating temperature is determined,  we presented the inflationary predictions for the spectral index and the tensor-to-scalar ratio, depending on the reheating dynamics. 
In particular, in the $B-L$ Higgs inflation, when the light inflaton has a small Higgs-portal coupling, the reheating temperature is small, so the reheating dynamics affects much the inflationary predictions if the equation of state deviates from radiation. 


